textDisplay:
Agree with much of what Elon says, and I think he is in error in significant ways. He demonstrates a failure to sufficiently understand the strategic underpinnings of evolution; which is not surprising because he has been so focused on other areas (necessarily) and the evolution of complex systems is a deeply complex subject (one that has occupied most of my autistic brain's attention for over 50 years).

At about 13:30 Elon warns against too much cooperation.
I think he is in error there.
I agree with him that we do not want hegemony at any level. But hegemony and cooperation are not in any way the same thing - they are in many aspects opposites. So he is over simplifying something deeply complex.
What we need is genuine cooperation in diversity - with the genuinely diverse agents agreeing to accept and respect each other; agreeing that there are ecological and physical limits that we need to keep within if we wish to survive (even if we have some disagreement about where they might actually be in any specific context).
In this sense, it is not cooperation that is the danger, cooperation is essential to survival.
What is the danger is any level of failure to accept the necessity of diversity and complexity.

Cooperation in diversity is essential - fundamental, to our long term survival.

Any sort of hegemony, orthodoxy, certainty of truth, is the enemy of freedom and a threat to our long term survival.
Any agent that truly believes that they have found "Truth" will fail to look beyond it, because - why would you bother?

In this sense, it is the very notion of "Truth" itself, that is the enemy of freedom and survival.

What we all need is something with vastly more humility.


What we need is the idea of "useful approximation", a much "softer" form of "truth", which acknowledges that reality seems very probably to be more complex than any computational entity can deal with in detail, and thus we must all make our simplistic approximations of it, and the role of science is to allow us to become "less wrong" over time, without ever expecting to be "Right". But evolution supplies us with brains strongly biased to simplify everything down to simple binaries like "Right"/"Wrong", good/evil, true/false; rather than accept an infinite set of infinities, with all their graduations and uncertainties and eternal ignorance. The more stressed we are, at any level, the greater such biases become.

In this sense, removing stress, is fundamental to the possibility of education - at any and all levels.
And that is a deeply subtle and recursive idea.


Around 25 minutes:
Agree about education, and one of the fundamental things that needs to be taught is the eternal need for freedom and responsibility - the eternal need to find balance between search of the unknown and respect for the boundaries necessary to maintain the complexities essential to existence - recursively, all levels, all domains! Every level of structure requires boundaries. Hard boundaries tend to become brittle and break - you do not see such things in biology.


At the end, agree that the Fermi paradox is a concern.
My prime candidate for explaining it, is that evolution has a strong set of incentives to select for intelligence that is strongly biased to simplify at all levels.
This tends to lead to an over simplification of the concept of evolution itself, such that the orthodox view becomes that evolution is all about competition; and there is a general failure to accept the deeper and much more complex reality that at every level of complexity, it is cooperation that is fundamental to both the emergence and long term survival of complexity.
It is that failure to accept the reality of complexity, and a tendency which increases with stress and urgency, to over simplify the reality around us; that leads to failure.
Competition is a real and essential part of evolution, and unless it is built upon a cooperative base, it necessarily destroys the level of complexity that made it possible (recursively).
That is, in my understanding, the prime cause of failure of civilizations, and the most probable reason for us not seeing intelligence all around us.

It is also possible that we live in a galactic "conservation park" and we have not yet passed the threshold test of galactic intelligence that would allow us to emerge from it and be accepted as members of galactic society.

In a very real sense, both are essentially the same thing. When one starts to gain a useful approximation of an understanding of the depths of the strategic complexity underpinning evolution, over simplification and aggression are existential level threats.

At about 13:30 Elon warns against too much cooperation.
I think he is in error there.
I agree with him that we do not want hegemony at any level.   But hegemony and cooperation are not in any way the same thing - they are in many aspects opposites.   So he is over simplifying something deeply complex.

textDisplay:
The ICEV fleet (at least 95%) should disappear within a decade after the start of sales of acceptable range EVs selling for no more than $25k. There will be a rapid drop in fueling stations and ICEV repair shops. Owning an ICEV will become less convenient and the savings provided by EVs will cause ICEVs to be sent to the crusher at a younger age than what we now see.

One pressure pretty much no one is seeing is the impact of <$10k EVs on the used car market. Cheap EVs, of which there are at least five Chinese brands, will destroy demand for used ICEVs in less developed countries. Why pay the cost of shipping a used "Camry" along with the cost of the car and the cost of fuel/maintenance when EVs will be so cheap and cheap to operate? When used ICEVs have no market value beyond their recycled material cost we'll see owners driving their ICEVs longer, decreasing new ICEV demand.

textDisplay:
@B Joy
Demand.

Assume it costs Tesla less than $5k to manufacture and they sell for $20k. The bots will be able to work 24/365 and should last more than ten years, but let's use ten. $20k / 10 years / 365 days / 24 hours = $0.23/hour.

By definition a humanoid robot with artificial intelligence should be able to do anything a human can do, only better. No bathroom and meal breaks, no sick days, no wandering attention, no forgetfulness. No fatigue.

If an individual purchased a bot and had only enough work for an eight hour day (housekeeping, mowing the lawn, cooking, etc.) the bot's labor would cost less than $1/hour.

Demand will be immense.

textDisplay:
@B Joy
Let's first think about what is in a humanoid robot. There's a "skeleton" which will be made out of some sturdy, lightweight material like aluminum or a composite. Some actuators to make the system move. A CPU, cameras and other sensors, and a battery pack. Cover it all up with some sort of 'skin'.

These things will be built in large quantities. Quickly. Demand, once they are working will be immense. Now, how to price it out.

The skeleton and skin. Small money. Probably less than $200.

The CPU. I think the Tesla EV CPU is only a few hundred dollars. Cameras are really cheap. The actuators Tesla has shown shouldn't cost a lot each when manufactured at scale. If they cost $100 each that's about $3k. A 2.3 kWh battery pack should cost less than $200.

My napkin math says somewhere between $2k and $5k for the parts.

Or do it another way. The Tesla 3 weighs 3,648 pounds and costs about $35,000 to manufacture (rough number). That's about $10/pound. The Tesla bot is supposed to weigh 160 pounds which would mean $1,600, manufactured. That's likely low but it tells us that the manufactured cost is likely to be in the low thousands.

textDisplay: @Bob Wallace How cheap is your phone? Probably somewhere more than $200? It is full of commoditized elements and has no moving pieces. Now, create a robot that packs in far more tech than a phone and it moves and it has to be able to move around under it's own power. It's going to cost a hell of a lot until everyone is buying their own like we buy cars. How long will that take? 50 years to become a high volume item that everyone buys at least one robot each decade? Anyone thinking that robots have a place outside of robo taxis and as factory worker replacements is fooling themselves if they think it's coming soon.
